modules.name: AWS.DAX
modules.comments: DAX is a managed caching service engineered for Amazon DynamoDB. DAX dramatically speeds up database reads by caching frequently-accessed data from DynamoDB, so applications can access that data with sub-millisecond latency. You can create a DAX cluster easily, using the AWS Management Console. With a few simple modifications to your code, your application can begin taking advantage of the DAX cluster and realize significant improvements in read performance.

declarations.comments: Creates a DAX cluster. All nodes in the cluster run the same DAX caching software.
declarations.title: createCluster

declarations.comments: Creates a new parameter group. A parameter group is a collection of parameters that you apply to all of the nodes in a DAX cluster.
declarations.title: createParameterGroup

declarations.comments: Creates a new subnet group.
declarations.title: createSubnetGroup

declarations.comments:
Removes one or more nodes from a DAX cluster.

You cannot use DecreaseReplicationFactor to remove the last node in a DAX cluster. If you need to do this, use DeleteCluster instead.
declarations.title: decreaseReplicationFactor

declarations.comments: Deletes a previously provisioned DAX cluster. DeleteCluster deletes all associated nodes, node endpoints and the DAX cluster itself. When you receive a successful response from this action, DAX immediately begins deleting the cluster; you cannot cancel or revert this action.
declarations.title: deleteCluster

declarations.comments: Deletes the specified parameter group. You cannot delete a parameter group if it is associated with any DAX clusters.
declarations.title: deleteParameterGroup

declarations.comments:
Deletes a subnet group.

You cannot delete a subnet group if it is associated with any DAX clusters.
declarations.title: deleteSubnetGroup

declarations.comments:
Returns information about all provisioned DAX clusters if no cluster identifier is specified, or about a specific DAX cluster if a cluster identifier is supplied.

If the cluster is in the CREATING state, only cluster level information will be displayed until all of the nodes are successfully provisioned.

If the cluster is in the DELETING state, only cluster level information will be displayed.

If nodes are currently being added to the DAX cluster, node endpoint information and creation time for the additional nodes will not be displayed until they are completely provisioned. When the DAX cluster state is available, the cluster is ready for use.

If nodes are currently being removed from the DAX cluster, no endpoint information for the removed nodes is displayed.
declarations.title: describeClusters

declarations.comments: Returns the default system parameter information for the DAX caching software.
declarations.title: describeDefaultParameters

declarations.comments:
Returns events related to DAX clusters and parameter groups. You can obtain events specific to a particular DAX cluster or parameter group by providing the name as a parameter.

By default, only the events occurring within the last hour are returned; however, you can retrieve up to 14 days' worth of events if necessary.
declarations.title: describeEvents

declarations.comments: Returns a list of parameter group descriptions. If a parameter group name is specified, the list will contain only the descriptions for that group.
declarations.title: describeParameterGroups

declarations.comments: Returns the detailed parameter list for a particular parameter group.
declarations.title: describeParameters

declarations.comments: Returns a list of subnet group descriptions. If a subnet group name is specified, the list will contain only the description of that group.
declarations.title: describeSubnetGroups

declarations.comments: Adds one or more nodes to a DAX cluster.
declarations.title: increaseReplicationFactor

declarations.comments: List all of the tags for a DAX cluster. You can call ListTags up to 10 times per second, per account.
declarations.title: listTags

declarations.comments: Reboots a single node of a DAX cluster. The reboot action takes place as soon as possible. During the reboot, the node status is set to REBOOTING.
declarations.title: rebootNode

declarations.comments: Associates a set of tags with a DAX resource. You can call TagResource up to 5 times per second, per account.
declarations.title: tagResource

declarations.comments: Removes the association of tags from a DAX resource. You can call UntagResource up to 5 times per second, per account.
declarations.title: untagResource

declarations.comments: Modifies the settings for a DAX cluster. You can use this action to change one or more cluster configuration parameters by specifying the parameters and the new values.
declarations.title: updateCluster

declarations.comments: Modifies the parameters of a parameter group. You can modify up to 20 parameters in a single request by submitting a list parameter name and value pairs.
declarations.title: updateParameterGroup

declarations.comments: Modifies an existing subnet group.
declarations.title: updateSubnetGroup

declarations.comments: Contains all of the attributes of a specific DAX cluster.
declarations.title: Cluster

declarations.comments: You already have a DAX cluster with the given identifier.
declarations.title: ClusterAlreadyExistsFault

declarations.comments: The requested cluster ID does not refer to an existing DAX cluster.
declarations.title: ClusterNotFoundFault

declarations.comments: You have attempted to exceed the maximum number of DAX clusters for your AWS account.
declarations.title: ClusterQuotaForCustomerExceededFault

declarations.comments: Represents the information required for client programs to connect to the configuration endpoint for a DAX cluster, or to an individual node within the cluster.
declarations.title: Endpoint

declarations.comments: Represents a single occurrence of something interesting within the system. Some examples of events are creating a DAX cluster, adding or removing a node, or rebooting a node.
declarations.title: Event

declarations.comments: There are not enough system resources to create the cluster you requested (or to resize an already-existing cluster).
declarations.title: InsufficientClusterCapacityFault

declarations.comments: The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) supplied in the request is not valid.
declarations.title: InvalidARNFault

declarations.comments: The requested DAX cluster is not in the available state.
declarations.title: InvalidClusterStateFault

declarations.comments: Two or more incompatible parameters were specified.
declarations.title: InvalidParameterCombinationException

declarations.comments: One or more parameters in a parameter group are in an invalid state.
declarations.title: InvalidParameterGroupStateFault

declarations.comments: The value for a parameter is invalid.
declarations.title: InvalidParameterValueException

declarations.comments: An invalid subnet identifier was specified.
declarations.title: InvalidSubnet

declarations.comments: The VPC network is in an invalid state.
declarations.title: InvalidVPCNetworkStateFault

declarations.comments: Represents an individual node within a DAX cluster.
declarations.title: Node

declarations.comments: None of the nodes in the cluster have the given node ID.
declarations.title: NodeNotFoundFault

declarations.comments: You have attempted to exceed the maximum number of nodes for a DAX cluster.
declarations.title: NodeQuotaForClusterExceededFault

declarations.comments: You have attempted to exceed the maximum number of nodes for your AWS account.
declarations.title: NodeQuotaForCustomerExceededFault

declarations.comments: Represents a parameter value that is applicable to a particular node type.
declarations.title: NodeTypeSpecificValue

declarations.comments: Describes a notification topic and its status. Notification topics are used for publishing DAX events to subscribers using Amazon Simple Notification Service (SNS).
declarations.title: NotificationConfiguration

declarations.comments: Describes an individual setting that controls some aspect of DAX behavior.
declarations.title: Parameter

declarations.comments: A named set of parameters that are applied to all of the nodes in a DAX cluster.
declarations.title: ParameterGroup

declarations.comments: The specified parameter group already exists.
declarations.title: ParameterGroupAlreadyExistsFault

declarations.comments: The specified parameter group does not exist.
declarations.title: ParameterGroupNotFoundFault

declarations.comments: You have attempted to exceed the maximum number of parameter groups.
declarations.title: ParameterGroupQuotaExceededFault

declarations.comments: The status of a parameter group.
declarations.title: ParameterGroupStatus

declarations.comments: An individual DAX parameter.
declarations.title: ParameterNameValue

declarations.comments: An individual VPC security group and its status.
declarations.title: SecurityGroupMembership

declarations.comments: Represents the subnet associated with a DAX cluster. This parameter refers to subnets defined in Amazon Virtual Private Cloud (Amazon VPC) and used with DAX.
declarations.title: Subnet

declarations.comments:
Represents the output of one of the following actions:

  • CreateSubnetGroup

  • ModifySubnetGroup
declarations.title: SubnetGroup

declarations.comments: The specified subnet group already exists.
declarations.title: SubnetGroupAlreadyExistsFault

declarations.comments: The specified subnet group is currently in use.
declarations.title: SubnetGroupInUseFault

declarations.comments: The requested subnet group name does not refer to an existing subnet group.
declarations.title: SubnetGroupNotFoundFault

declarations.comments: The request cannot be processed because it would exceed the allowed number of subnets in a subnet group.
declarations.title: SubnetGroupQuotaExceededFault

declarations.comments: The requested subnet is being used by another subnet group.
declarations.title: SubnetInUse

declarations.comments: The request cannot be processed because it would exceed the allowed number of subnets in a subnet group.
declarations.title: SubnetQuotaExceededFault

declarations.comments:
A description of a tag. Every tag is a key-value pair. You can add up to 50 tags to a single DAX cluster.

AWS-assigned tag names and values are automatically assigned the aws: prefix, which the user cannot assign. AWS-assigned tag names do not count towards the tag limit of 50. User-assigned tag names have the prefix user:.

You cannot backdate the application of a tag.
declarations.title: Tag

declarations.comments: The tag does not exist.
declarations.title: TagNotFoundFault

declarations.comments: You have exceeded the maximum number of tags for this DAX cluster.
declarations.title: TagQuotaPerResourceExceeded
